"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"This is as good as it gets, for what it is. It&#39;s never going to be Joel Robuchon in Vegas, but it doesn&#39;t want to be. The space is fluorescent, loud, and the videos are playing music in Arabic. The atmosphere is spartan, but convivial.  And the waitstaff attentive and proud of their product. They should be. The product is great.<br><br>Made a first visit here on Friday to see what the hoopla and 388 yelp reviews were all about. We were four people, and ordered the feast for two, plus the lamb chops. <br><br>The salads were fragrant and homemade. The hummus smoother than Marlene Dietrich&#39;s voice. The baba ganoush mouth watering. The falafels crisp on the outside, and somehow not dry inside. Grade: A.<br><br>Then came the meats. The chicken. Maybe the best ever chicken kabob, why also were not dry.  The lamb was succulent. And it all came on a hill of rice that was impossible to make a dent in. It seemed to regenerate as we ate it.<br><br>The kicker was the complimentary baklava at the end. Better than any, ever. Not drippying goo. Just scrumptious, like the final note of Beethoven&#39;s fifth. <br><br>Have tried a number of Lebanese places in multiple cities. This is the best yet. <br><br>Sat inside, but there&#39;s outdoor seating too.<br><br>Total bill for four, with tip: $70.  That&#39;s with tea, drinks, etc.",
