"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Like many others, I discovered this place after the Mark Bittman article in the New York Times.  It&#39;s now framed in the restaurant so you can point it out to newcomers.  I&#39;ve brought hordes of newcomers, and urged many of my friends to try this place because it&#39;s delicious, and we need to support the non-chains.  I&#39;ve sent a lot of repeat customers to Adana.<br><br>So when my in-laws visited from NYC and mentioned they have never had Armenian food, I knew we had to scratch that off their bucket list.  They are not foodies nor adventurous eaters -- can&#39;t use chopsticks, hold the sushi, just Uncle Ben&#39;s converted rice.  These creatures of habit loved everything they sampled, from the hummus to the Persian salad.  As we made our exit, my mother in law told Edward they&#39;d like to come back on their next visit.   Whew.  Score one for the daughter-in-law.<br><br>We&#39;ve enjoyed many dishes since July 2013:  lamb chops, pork ribs, cornish hen, beef koobideh, chicken koobideh, honeycake.  The ikra is the best, and I often order it to go for holidays where it&#39;s always a hit and great advertisement for Adana.   <br><br>There&#39;s still no real signage, which is ironic since it&#39;s next door to the sign store.  <br><br>There is a new menu, Edward continues to innovate and remind of me some dishes I need to try.  As one would expect, the prices have risen since that NYTimes review, about 30% since last July.  Happy for them, a little sad for financially challenged me, but hopefully success breeds success.",
